    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nfollowup work https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/36397#issuecomment-4150379418 : \n\n- [ ] Test coverage could be stronger for the `to_inclusive_pos` logic and edge cases.\n- [x] `Pos.to_extmark` fetches all buffer lines (`#api.nvim_buf_get_lines(pos.buf, 0, -1, true)`) just to get the line count. Use `nvim_buf_line_count()` instead?  https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/38686\n- [ ] `Range.cursor` signature mismatch with docs. The example won't work as written.\n- [ ] `Range.to_extmark/to_cursor` create temporary `vim.Pos` objects. This partially defeats the performance motivation?\n- [x] `Range.extmark` validation names: all four `validate()` calls use 'range' as the parameter name instead of the actual parameter names ('start_row', 'start_col', etc.).\n- [ ] Breaking change to `Range.has` semantics: Tests only cover one case (`vim.range(0,0,0,4):has(vim.range(0,0,0,0))`). More edge cases would be valuable.\n- [ ] `intersect` loses `buf`: `Range.new(rs.start_row, rs.start_col, re.end_row, re.end_col)` doesn't pass opts, so the resulting range has no buf even if both inputs had one.\n- [ ] ⚠️ drop friendly keys / metatable. [ref](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/36397#discussion_r3006380267)\n- [ ] add tests for `intersect`\n- [x]  ⚠️ [require `buf` everywhere?](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/36397#discussion_r3006323346) https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/38665\n    - also [consistent (buf, row, col) ordering](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/36397#discussion_r3006332479)\n- [ ]  [use integer indexing internally](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/36397#discussion_r3006324626) for perf\n- [ ]  docs: [callout integer indexing](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/36397#discussion_r3006319572)\n- [ ] support `buf=0` to mean \"current buffer\"? `vim.pos(0)`, `:extmark(0,...)`, etc. [ref](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/38665#discussion_r3040287364)\n- [ ] support `opts.win=0` to mean \"current win\"?\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nsee above\n\ncc @TheLeoP \n",
